INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(444,'new-south-wales-adam-crouch-terrigal','voluntary_assisted_dying','Adam Crouch voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(445,'new-south-wales-michael-daley-maroubra','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(446,'new-south-wales-michael-daley-maroubra','voluntary_assisted_dying','Michael Daley voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(447,'new-south-wales-michael-daley-maroubra','religious_freedom','As Attorney General, Daley introduced and championed the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024 (passed 22 March 2024). He said conversion practices ''cause significant ongoing trauma'' and that the law was developed ''following extensive consultation to ensure that it strikes the right balance between protecting vulnerable communities as well as legitimate religious and cultural practices,'' adding the government did ''not intend to ban the teachings of a religious leader or expression of a religious belief through sermon.'' He later reaffirmed in parliament that ''praying with or over a particular person in an attempt to try to change or suppress that person''s sexuality or gender is unlawful.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(448,'new-south-wales-michael-daley-maroubra','drugs_law_order','Labor Attorney-General. He announced the 2024 youth bail law changes and the new "post and boast" (performance crime) offence (passed 22 March 2024), saying the bail laws were "purposefully designed to address repeated alleged offending by young people aged between 14 and 18" and that posting footage advertising crimes "is unacceptable and has to stop." He supported the expansion of pre-court drug diversion (Early Drug Diversion Initiative), calling it "key to alleviating pressure on our court system," and led the Government''s October 2025 response to the 2024 Drug Summit which supported over 50 of 56 recommendations including a pill-testing trial and reformed drug diversion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(449,'new-south-wales-helen-dalton-murray','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(450,'new-south-wales-helen-dalton-murray','voluntary_assisted_dying','Helen Dalton voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(451,'new-south-wales-tanya-davies-badgerys-creek','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(452,'new-south-wales-tanya-davies-badgerys-creek','voluntary_assisted_dying','Tanya Davies voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(453,'new-south-wales-tanya-davies-badgerys-creek','religious_freedom','Davies (Liberal MP), a member of the party''s conservative faction, tabled a petition in the Legislative Assembly on 10 October 2023 (3,148 signatures) calling on the government to refer the proposed conversion-therapy legislation to a Joint Parliamentary Select Committee ''to ensure that the Government honours its Election Promises.'' The petition urged protection of religious teaching, prayer and guidance on gender and sexuality, inclusion of faith leaders in drafting, and a clear distinction between coercive practices and religious interventions.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(454,'new-south-wales-jihad-dib-bankstown','faith','Jihad Dib is Muslim; he was the first Muslim elected to the NSW Legislative Assembly and took his oath on his own Qur''an, a first in that chamber.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(455,'new-south-wales-jihad-dib-bankstown','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(456,'new-south-wales-jihad-dib-bankstown','voluntary_assisted_dying','Jihad Dib voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(457,'new-south-wales-philip-donato-orange','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(458,'new-south-wales-philip-donato-orange','voluntary_assisted_dying','Philip Donato voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(459,'new-south-wales-trish-doyle-blue-mountains','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(460,'new-south-wales-trish-doyle-blue-mountains','voluntary_assisted_dying','Trish Doyle voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(461,'new-south-wales-julia-finn-granville','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote; not recorded in the second reading division.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(462,'new-south-wales-julia-finn-granville','voluntary_assisted_dying','Julia Finn voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(463,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(464,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','voluntary_assisted_dying','Alex Greenwich voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(465,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','gender_lgbtq','Independent MP for Sydney and an openly gay member of the NSW Legislative Assembly (married to Victor Hoeld). A leading LGBTIQ law-reform advocate: former co-chair of Australian Marriage Equality and a key leader of the 2017 ''Yes'' marriage equality campaign. He introduced and championed the Equality Legislation Amendment (LGBTIQA+) Bill 2023, which passed the Legislative Assembly 50 votes to 30 (16 Oct 2024) and the Legislative Council 15-12 (17 Oct 2024) in amended form, removing barriers to gender recognition (allowing trans people to change birth certificates without surgery). He described the decision to strip back parts of the bill as ''heartbreaking.'' In Sept 2024 the Federal Court found a tweet by Mark Latham about Greenwich was defamatory and homophobic, awarding him $140,000.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(466,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','religious_freedom','Greenwich (Independent MP) dissented from the parliamentary committee report endorsing Mark Latham''s religious-freedom bill and, with Jenny Leong, urged the Attorney-General to disregard it, warning against enshrining protections for discrimination ''under the guise of religious freedoms.'' He championed the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024, saying on its passage that ''NSW wakes up a safer place for LGBTQIA+ people.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(467,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','drugs_law_order','Independent MP for Sydney who advocates drug law reform. He supports decriminalisation as a harm-reduction approach (replacing convictions with cautions, fines and health referrals), pill testing, and removing the possibility of custodial sentences for adults possessing small quantities of cannabis. He has disclosed holding a medicinal cannabis prescription, saying "Like over 100,000 people in NSW, I have a script for medical cannabis. It helps me manage anxiety and insomnia," and has campaigned for a medical defence so prescribed cannabis users are not penalised for driving when unimpaired, noting "THC can be detected for days, if not weeks, after it no longer impacts driving."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(468,'new-south-wales-alex-greenwich-sydney','gambling','Leading parliamentary advocate for mandatory cashless gaming on poker machines in NSW as a harm-minimisation and anti-money-laundering measure. Vowed to legislate cashless gaming regardless of which party won the 2023 election, saying ''Cashless gaming is going to pass the New South Wales parliament whether the Labor party likes it or not,'' and pledging to introduce his own private member''s bill if government did not act. Supported the Coalition''s plan to make all pokies cashless by 2028 and criticised Labor''s more limited 500-machine trial.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(469,'new-south-wales-james-griffin-manly','voluntary_assisted_dying','James Griffin voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(470,'new-south-wales-david-harris-wyong','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(471,'new-south-wales-david-harris-wyong','voluntary_assisted_dying','David Harris voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(472,'new-south-wales-david-harris-wyong','gambling','As NSW Minister for Gaming and Racing, oversaw the government''s staged gaming-reform roadmap, including the March 2024 cashless gaming trial and the Independent Panel on Gaming Reform. Stated: ''The NSW Government is committed to gambling reform that reduces harm and prevents money laundering in NSW,'' describing the trial as ''a key step for these reforms,'' while pursuing a measured, panel-guided approach rather than an immediate statewide mandate.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(473,'new-south-wales-jodie-harrison-charlestown','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(474,'new-south-wales-jodie-harrison-charlestown','voluntary_assisted_dying','Jodie Harrison voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(475,'new-south-wales-jo-haylen-summer-hill','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(476,'new-south-wales-jo-haylen-summer-hill','voluntary_assisted_dying','Jo Haylen voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(477,'new-south-wales-alister-henskens-wahroonga','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the second reading (8 Aug 2019) but in favour of the amended bill at the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(478,'new-south-wales-alister-henskens-wahroonga','voluntary_assisted_dying','Alister Henskens voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(479,'new-south-wales-alister-henskens-wahroonga','drugs_law_order','Liberal MP who, as a shadow minister, introduced the private member''s Bail Amendment (Serious Personal Violence and Electronic Monitoring) Bill 2024 in the Legislative Assembly on 9 May 2024. The bill sought to expand electronic monitoring for bail on serious personal violence charges and to restrict local court registrars from granting bail for such offences. The bill lapsed under Standing Orders on 8 November 2024.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(480,'new-south-wales-ron-hoenig-heffron','faith','Ron Hoenig is Jewish and a member of the Maroubra Synagogue.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(481,'new-south-wales-ron-hoenig-heffron','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
