INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(484,'new-south-wales-sonia-hornery-wallsend','voluntary_assisted_dying','Sonia Hornery voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(485,'new-south-wales-steve-kamper-rockdale','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(486,'new-south-wales-steve-kamper-rockdale','voluntary_assisted_dying','Steve Kamper voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(487,'new-south-wales-dave-layzell-upper-hunter','voluntary_assisted_dying','Dave Layzell voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(488,'new-south-wales-jenny-leong-newtown','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(489,'new-south-wales-jenny-leong-newtown','voluntary_assisted_dying','Jenny Leong voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(490,'new-south-wales-jenny-leong-newtown','gender_lgbtq','Greens MP for Newtown who supported LGBTIQ equality but criticised the scaled-back Equality Legislation Amendment (LGBTIQA+) Bill 2024, saying the reduced bill ''leaves the queer community vulnerable.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(491,'new-south-wales-jenny-leong-newtown','religious_freedom','Leong (Greens MP) dissented from the parliamentary committee report that endorsed Mark Latham''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment (Religious Freedoms and Equality) Bill, and with Alex Greenwich wrote to the Attorney-General urging him to disregard the report. She said ''there is a need to protect people from being discriminated against on the basis of their religious beliefs, but that is not the same as enshrining protections for people to engage in whole scale discrimination against women and the LGBTIQ+ community under the guise of religious freedoms.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(492,'new-south-wales-hugh-mcdermott-prospect','faith','Hugh McDermott holds a strong belief in Catholic social teaching, once considered joining the priesthood, and spoke of his admiration for Jesuits in his inaugural speech.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(493,'new-south-wales-hugh-mcdermott-prospect','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(494,'new-south-wales-joe-mcgirr-wagga-wagga','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(495,'new-south-wales-joe-mcgirr-wagga-wagga','voluntary_assisted_dying','Joe McGirr voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(496,'new-south-wales-david-mehan-entrance','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(497,'new-south-wales-david-mehan-entrance','voluntary_assisted_dying','David Mehan voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(498,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','faith','Chris Minns has spoken candidly about his Catholic faith, describing himself as a member of the Christian ''missionary faith'' and emphasising the public celebration of Christianity.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(499,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(500,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','voluntary_assisted_dying','Chris Minns voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(501,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','religious_freedom','Premier Minns'' government introduced the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024 (announced 13 March 2024, passed 22 March 2024). The government said it developed the legislation ''following extensive consultation'' to balance protecting vulnerable communities with ''legitimate religious and cultural practices,'' and stated it did not intend to ban religious teaching or expression of belief through a sermon.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(502,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','drugs_law_order','Labor Premier. As Opposition Leader before the March 2023 election he supported a drug summit, pill testing, decriminalisation of personal drug use and cannabis law reform, but as Premier announced at the December 2024 NSW Drug Summit that decriminalisation was "off the table," arguing he had no mandate. He championed police knife "wanding" powers (modelled on Queensland''s Jack''s Law), saying at their December 2024 commencement that the laws would be "inconvenient" but "we can''t take chances when it comes to public safety." He defended and extended the youth bail laws in February 2025, stating "the bail laws are working, so we''re extending them."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(503,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','nuclear','As NSW Premier, refused to lift the state''s ban on nuclear power in response to the federal Coalition''s June 2024 nuclear plan, questioning the cost and whether the Commonwealth could constitutionally force states to build reactors.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(504,'new-south-wales-chris-minns-kogarah','housing_planning','As Premier, Minns backed the Minns Labor Government''s landmark 2024 rental reforms ending no-grounds evictions and capping rent increases to once a year, while stressing landlords retained the ability to evict bad tenants: ''Bad tenants will still be able to be evicted. We don''t want homeowners to have (to) put up with bad behaviour.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(505,'new-south-wales-marjorie-o-neill-coogee','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(506,'new-south-wales-marjorie-o-neill-coogee','voluntary_assisted_dying','Marjorie O''Neill voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(507,'new-south-wales-ryan-park-keira','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(508,'new-south-wales-ryan-park-keira','voluntary_assisted_dying','Ryan Park voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(509,'new-south-wales-ryan-park-keira','religious_freedom','As Minister for Health, Park was named among ministers supporting the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024, which the government stated was developed to balance protecting vulnerable communities with ''legitimate religious and cultural practices,'' and did not intend to ban religious teaching or expression of belief through a sermon.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(510,'new-south-wales-ryan-park-keira','drugs_law_order','Labor Minister for Health. Following the December 2024 NSW Drug Summit he announced a 12-month pill/drug checking trial at music festivals starting early 2025, saying "if there are any further steps we can take to keep young people safe this festival season we''ll listen" and that the Government "will be guided by that which delivers in the best interests of the health of the community." In the October 2025 Drug Summit response he described drug reform as traversing "health, law and order, education, housing and so much more."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(511,'new-south-wales-ryan-park-keira','health','NSW Minister for Health (Minns Labor government, since 2023). Oversaw the return of Northern Beaches Hospital to full public operation in April 2026, calling it ''a historic day for the people of the Northern Beaches and for the NSW public health system'' and framing it as reversing a privatisation failure; the government is establishing the state''s first High Volume Planned Surgery Centre there to cut surgery wait times. Stated health priorities are improving access to care in cities and regional NSW, boosting the health workforce and investing in health infrastructure.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(512,'new-south-wales-eleni-petinos-miranda','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Assembly, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at both the second reading (8 Aug 2019) and the third reading (final passage, 8 Aug 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
