INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(555,'new-south-wales-felicity-wilson-north-shore','voluntary_assisted_dying','Felicity Wilson voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Assembly on 26 November 2021 (Assembly third reading, which passed 52 votes to 32). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(556,'new-south-wales-felicity-wilson-north-shore','gender_lgbtq','Liberal MP for North Shore. She crossed the floor to support the Equality Legislation Amendment (LGBTIQA+) Bill 2024, defying Liberal party lines (the party did not grant a conscience vote). She said: ''As a Liberal I believe in the fundamental principle of equality for all people, regardless of their gender identity or sexual orientation,'' and ''Just because the party won''t give you a conscience vote, doesn''t mean that you don''t have a conscience.'' She argued the bill ''will not harm any person in NSW'' and called claims it would create risk for women ''fearmongering.'' She had previously supported the ''Yes'' vote for marriage equality.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(557,'new-south-wales-mark-banasiak-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(558,'new-south-wales-mark-banasiak-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Mark Banasiak voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(559,'new-south-wales-mark-banasiak-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(560,'new-south-wales-robert-borsak-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(561,'new-south-wales-robert-borsak-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Robert Borsak voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(562,'new-south-wales-robert-borsak-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(563,'new-south-wales-abigail-boyd-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(564,'new-south-wales-abigail-boyd-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Abigail Boyd voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(565,'new-south-wales-abigail-boyd-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(566,'new-south-wales-jeremy-buckingham-statewide','drugs_law_order','Legalise Cannabis Party MLC and the party''s first NSW member, elected 2023. A leading cannabis-reform advocate, he introduced the Drug Misuse and Trafficking Amendment (Regulation of Personal Adult Use of Cannabis) Bill 2023 in the Legislative Council on 29 November 2023, which would let adults possess small quantities of cannabis, cultivate up to six plants and gift cannabis to other adults (debate adjourned at second reading). He chaired Portfolio Committee No. 1''s inquiry into the cannabis regulatory framework (appointed 20 March 2024); its final report (20 June 2025) called existing cannabis laws "unjust and ineffective" and recommended abolishing custodial sentences for minor possession and a staged move toward decriminalisation and legal regulated access.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(567,'new-south-wales-jeremy-buckingham-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(568,'new-south-wales-mark-buttigieg-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(569,'new-south-wales-mark-buttigieg-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Mark Buttigieg voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(570,'new-south-wales-mark-buttigieg-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(571,'new-south-wales-susan-carter-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Liberal MLC who argued against the Equality Legislation Amendment (LGBTIQA+) Bill 2024, citing concerns about single-sex spaces. She was also among the members who moved or supported amendments during the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024 debate.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(572,'new-south-wales-susan-carter-statewide','religious_freedom','Carter (Liberal MLC) used parliamentary questioning to scrutinise the religious-freedom impact of the Conversion Practices Ban Act 2024, asking Attorney General Michael Daley whether the law makes some prayers unlawful even when people freely seek them; in response Daley confirmed that ''praying with or over a particular person in an attempt to try to change or suppress that person''s sexuality or gender is unlawful.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(573,'new-south-wales-susan-carter-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(574,'new-south-wales-amanda-cohn-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(575,'new-south-wales-amanda-cohn-statewide','health','NSW Greens MLC, Greens spokesperson for Health and Mental Health, and Chair of Portfolio Committee No. 2 - Health. A GP and former rural emergency-services worker, she campaigns for legislated nurse-to-patient ratios, saying ''we know that ratios save lives, they improve working conditions and are also cost saving'' and describing the NSW public health system as ''in absolute crisis.'' During the 2025 psychiatrist mass-resignation dispute she urged the Minns government to pay staff-specialist psychiatrists competitively rather than rely on costly locum agencies.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(576,'new-south-wales-anthony-d-adam-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Anthony D''Adam voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(577,'new-south-wales-anthony-d-adam-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(578,'new-south-wales-greg-donnelly-statewide','faith','Greg Donnelly is a Catholic and has been outspoken on matters associated with his faith, particularly pro-life advocacy.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(579,'new-south-wales-greg-donnelly-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(580,'new-south-wales-greg-donnelly-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Greg Donnelly voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(581,'new-south-wales-greg-donnelly-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Labor MLC (since 2005), a Catholic who has been a consistent opponent of LGBTQ-affirming legislation. He opposed a NSW Greens marriage equality bill (2012); in May 2017 was one of three Labor MPs to vote with the Coalition to block decriminalisation of abortion; wrote against same-sex adoption in NSW; and wrote an opinion piece opposing the Safe Schools program (Nov 2016). He publicly urged people to sign a petition calling on the Legislative Council to vote against Alex Greenwich''s Equality Bill, arguing the reforms risked ''far-reaching unintended consequences for women and children'' and would let ''males legally identify as females'' and access women-only spaces. In June 2023 he spoke at a ''Why Can''t Women Talk About Sex'' event alongside Moira Deeming and Tania Mihailuk.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(582,'new-south-wales-greg-donnelly-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
