INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(584,'new-south-wales-scott-farlow-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Scott Farlow voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(585,'new-south-wales-scott-farlow-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(586,'new-south-wales-cate-faehrmann-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(587,'new-south-wales-cate-faehrmann-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Cate Faehrmann voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(588,'new-south-wales-cate-faehrmann-statewide','drugs_law_order','Greens MLC and the party''s drug law reform and harm reduction spokesperson. In August 2023 she publicly advocated legalising cocaine in Australia, arguing "the war on drugs has failed." She supports legalising cannabis, allowing pill/drug checking, removing criminal sanctions for personal use and possession of all currently illicit drugs, ending the use of drug detection dogs, and repealing the roadside drug testing regime until it tests for impairment rather than mere presence.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(589,'new-south-wales-cate-faehrmann-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(590,'new-south-wales-wes-fang-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(591,'new-south-wales-wes-fang-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Wes Fang voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(592,'new-south-wales-wes-fang-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(593,'new-south-wales-ben-franklin-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(594,'new-south-wales-john-graham-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(595,'new-south-wales-john-graham-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','John Graham voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(596,'new-south-wales-john-graham-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(597,'new-south-wales-sue-higginson-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Sue Higginson voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(598,'new-south-wales-sue-higginson-statewide','drugs_law_order','Greens MLC and justice spokesperson who has consistently opposed the Minns Government''s youth bail law changes (section 22C of the Bail Act 2013). On the February 2025 three-year extension of the laws she said sending more young people to prison was "an indictment on the premier," criticising the government for gauging success on prison numbers. In an August 2025 statement she described the laws as "locking up more children and young people, for longer, before they have even been found guilty," noted nearly 60% of detained youth are First Nations, said "locking up kids is the most criminogenic thing we can do to them," and called instead to "invest in diversion, prevention, and community-led programs, not more prison beds for kids."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(599,'new-south-wales-sue-higginson-statewide','native_forest_logging','Greens MLC Higginson is a leading advocate for ending native forest logging in NSW, calling for the government to ''end native forest logging across NSW'' and to follow Western Australia and Victoria in halting operations. On the Great Koala National Park (7 Sep 2025) she said: ''We are jubilant that 176,000 hectares of our public native forests on the Mid North Coast are finally off the logging schedule.'' She has repeatedly described the Forestry Corporation as a ''serial offender.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(600,'new-south-wales-sue-higginson-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(601,'new-south-wales-courtney-houssos-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(602,'new-south-wales-courtney-houssos-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Courtney Houssos voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(603,'new-south-wales-courtney-houssos-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(604,'new-south-wales-emma-hurst-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(605,'new-south-wales-emma-hurst-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Emma Hurst voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(606,'new-south-wales-emma-hurst-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(607,'new-south-wales-rose-jackson-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Rose Jackson voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(608,'new-south-wales-rose-jackson-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(609,'new-south-wales-rose-jackson-statewide','housing_planning','As Minister for Housing and Homelessness, Jackson promoted the 2024 rental reforms ending no-grounds evictions, describing them as crucial to ''rebuilding our housing system'' and stating renters ''deserve more security and ending no grounds evictions is an important first step.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(610,'new-south-wales-sarah-kaine-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(611,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','faith','Mark Latham has described himself as a humanist and, in a 2004 interview, said ''I''m agnostic.'' In his 2019 NSW inaugural speech he stated ''I''m not a Christian but I recognise the vital contribution of Christianity to our civilisation.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(612,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(613,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Mark Latham voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(614,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','gender_lgbtq','One Nation MLC (sat as independent for part of the term) known for vocal opposition to transgender and LGBTIQ measures. He introduced the Education Legislation Amendment (Parental Rights) Bill, which sought to prohibit teaching of ''gender fluidity'' in schools, restrict trans students'' use of facilities and sports, and require school staff to disclose a student''s gender identity to parents; the NSW Government rejected it. During the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024 debate he opposed the late-night sitting, calling it a ''shameful tactic'' and the ''politics of exhaustion,'' and moved a motion to delay the debate. In Sept 2024 the Federal Court ruled a tweet he posted about Alex Greenwich was defamatory and homophobic.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(615,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','religious_freedom','Latham (One Nation MLC) has been a leading parliamentary advocate for religious-freedom and parental-rights legislation in NSW. He introduced the Anti-Discrimination Amendment (Religious Freedoms and Equality) Bill, which a NSW parliamentary committee chaired by Gabrielle Upton said had ''merit and could be used as a template for reform''; a version of the religious-freedom bill was defeated in the Legislative Council 29-4 in February 2022, with government and opposition uniting against it. He has also promoted an Education Legislation Amendment (Parental Rights) Bill to restrict teaching about gender, and in March 2023 gave a church speech on ''religious freedom, parental rights, school education.'' During the March 2024 conversion-practices debate he opposed the overnight sitting, calling it a ''shameful tactic'' and the ''politics of exhaustion.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(616,'new-south-wales-mark-latham-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(617,'new-south-wales-stephen-lawrence-statewide','drugs_law_order','Labor MLC and former Principal Legal Officer at the Aboriginal Legal Service (NSW/ACT). On the Government''s 2024 youth bail changes he said: "I think there should be changes to bail laws but it''s really important we look at long-term answers like programs," adding on crime and domestic violence that "this is a social problem and I try not to look at it in a sensational, simplistic way" and "I think we need to look at what works and build from there to find solutions."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(618,'new-south-wales-stephen-lawrence-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(619,'new-south-wales-aileen-macdonald-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(620,'new-south-wales-natasha-maclaren-jones-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(621,'new-south-wales-natasha-maclaren-jones-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(622,'new-south-wales-taylor-martin-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(623,'new-south-wales-taylor-martin-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Taylor Martin voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(624,'new-south-wales-taylor-martin-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(625,'new-south-wales-rachel-merton-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(626,'new-south-wales-tania-mihailuk-statewide','religious_freedom','Mihailuk (then Labor Member for Bankstown; later One Nation MLC) co-chaired the launch of the Parliamentary Friends for Religious Freedom Group in August 2019 alongside Liberal Damien Tudehope. At the launch she said, ''It''s important to understand that any religious discrimination law won''t replace anything in NSW.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(627,'new-south-wales-tania-mihailuk-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(628,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(629,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Sarah Mitchell voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(630,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Nationals MLC who, as NSW Education Minister (Perrottet Government), delivered the government''s response rejecting Mark Latham''s Education Legislation Amendment (Parental Rights) Bill (announced March 2022). She warned the bill had ''the potential to marginalise the LGBTIQ+ community, which is a group already experiencing increased isolation and vulnerability,'' and said ''the NSW Government supports the right of every student and teacher to be themselves at school.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(631,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(632,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','health','NSW Shadow Minister for Health, Regional Health and Mental Health (appointed January 2026 after Kellie Sloane became Opposition Leader). Argues the public health system is failing under Labor Health Minister Ryan Park, stating in March 2026 that ''our public health system is literally falling apart on Ryan Park''s watch'' and that ''it''s time to give someone else a go.'' Advocates for regional hospital investment and youth mental health facilities.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(633,'new-south-wales-sarah-mitchell-statewide','education','NSW Nationals MLC who served as Minister for Education and Early Childhood Learning (2019-2023) in the Berejiklian and Perrottet Coalition governments, and subsequently as Shadow Minister for Education and Early Learning in opposition. (A January 2026 shadow-ministry reshuffle reportedly moved education to Mark Speakman and Mitchell to health portfolios.)',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(634,'new-south-wales-daniel-mookhey-statewide','faith','Daniel Mookhey is Hindu; he took his oath of office as NSW Treasurer on the Bhagavad Gita in 2023, stating he was honoured to be the first Australian minister to do so.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(635,'new-south-wales-daniel-mookhey-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(636,'new-south-wales-daniel-mookhey-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Daniel Mookhey voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(637,'new-south-wales-daniel-mookhey-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(638,'new-south-wales-tara-moriarty-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(639,'new-south-wales-tara-moriarty-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Tara Moriarty voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(640,'new-south-wales-tara-moriarty-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(641,'new-south-wales-jacqui-munro-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Liberal MLC who spoke in support of the Equality Legislation Amendment (LGBTIQA+) Bill 2024 (although absent from the final vote). She said: ''I believe that gender fluidity and expression without medicalisation or formalised labels can and should be accepted.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(642,'new-south-wales-jacqui-munro-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(643,'new-south-wales-cameron-murphy-statewide','drugs_law_order','Labor MLC who voted for the Government''s 2024 youth bail bill in line with caucus solidarity but voiced personal objections in the Legislative Council, saying: "We in the Labor Party went to the last election on a platform that committed ... to closing the gap ... This bill, even though designed with the best intentions ... will ultimately send more Indigenous kids to jail."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(644,'new-south-wales-cameron-murphy-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(645,'new-south-wales-bob-nanva-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(646,'new-south-wales-peter-primrose-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(647,'new-south-wales-peter-primrose-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Peter Primrose voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(648,'new-south-wales-peter-primrose-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(649,'new-south-wales-chris-rath-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Chris Rath voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(650,'new-south-wales-chris-rath-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(651,'new-south-wales-rod-roberts-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(652,'new-south-wales-rod-roberts-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Rod Roberts voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(653,'new-south-wales-rod-roberts-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(654,'new-south-wales-john-ruddick-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Libertarian Party MLC, the first NSW Libertarian elected to Parliament (April 2023). During the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024 debate he moved an amendment to remove ''gender identity'' from the bill, prioritising individual autonomy in choosing counselling. He said: ''We support individuals or institutions offering a counselling service that attempts to convince people that they are not same-sex attracted or that they are not transgender,'' while adding he did not support practices involving ''physical assault or mental anguish'' as those are already crimes. The amendment was defeated.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(655,'new-south-wales-john-ruddick-statewide','nuclear','Introduced and moved the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 as a private member''s bill in the NSW Legislative Council and voted AYE on its second reading on 6 May 2026, seeking to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(656,'new-south-wales-penny-sharpe-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(657,'new-south-wales-penny-sharpe-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Penny Sharpe voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(658,'new-south-wales-penny-sharpe-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Labor MLC and Leader of the Government in the Legislative Council. She was the first openly lesbian member of the NSW Parliament (appointed 2005) and is a long-standing LGBTIQ rights advocate. She worked internally within Labor to shift the party toward supporting marriage equality and campaigned during the 2017 Marriage Law Postal Survey. In 2018 she championed cross-party amendments to the Public Health Act to establish abortion-clinic ''safe access zones.'' During the Equality Bill debate she defended the legislation, stating it ''does not impact on women''s rights.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(659,'new-south-wales-penny-sharpe-statewide','religious_freedom','As Leader of the Government in the Legislative Council, Sharpe was named among ministers supporting the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024, which the government said was crafted to balance protecting LGBTQ+ people with ''legitimate religious and cultural practices'' and not to ban religious teaching or expression of belief through a sermon.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(660,'new-south-wales-penny-sharpe-statewide','native_forest_logging','As NSW Environment Minister (ALP), Sharpe has led the Great Koala National Park process rather than a statewide logging ban. Regarding the park footprint she said ''We''re very close to finalising and announcing that,'' acknowledging the impact on logging (''there is going to be an impact'') and noting ''Koalas like the same large trees that our mills have relied on.'' Reporting indicates she accepts ''the status quo cannot continue'' on native forest logging. The government imposed a logging moratorium within the proposed park in Sep 2025.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(661,'new-south-wales-emily-suvaal-statewide','nuclear','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to keep NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill nonetheless passed 21–19.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(662,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','faith','Damien Tudehope is a Roman Catholic and a former spokesperson for the Australian Family Association.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(663,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted against the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(664,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Damien Tudehope voted against (Noes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(665,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','gender_lgbtq','Liberal MLC who criticised the process around the Conversion Practices Ban Bill 2024, with the all-night sitting timing described as an ''abuse of democracy.'' He was among Coalition members who sought amendments during the debate, including provisions around religious freedom.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(666,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','religious_freedom','Tudehope (Liberal MLC), then Coalition Minister for Finance, co-chaired the launch of the Parliamentary Friends for Religious Freedom Group in August 2019, a cross-party group of about 30 MPs that aimed to work toward drafting religious-freedom laws for NSW. During the March 2024 conversion-practices ban debate he objected to the late-night timing, saying ''This bill should not be starting at this hour of night.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(667,'new-south-wales-damien-tudehope-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(668,'new-south-wales-natalie-ward-statewide','abortion','As a member of the NSW Legislative Council, voted in favour of the Reproductive Health Care Reform Bill 2019 (which became the Abortion Law Reform Act 2019, decriminalising abortion in NSW) at the third reading (final passage, 25 Sept 2019), on a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(669,'new-south-wales-natalie-ward-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Natalie Ward voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(670,'new-south-wales-natalie-ward-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(671,'new-south-wales-scott-barrett-statewide','voluntary_assisted_dying','Scott Barrett voted in favour of (Ayes) the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 at its third reading in the Legislative Council on 19 May 2022 (Council third reading, which passed 23 votes to 15). The Act was a conscience vote and became the Voluntary Assisted Dying Act 2022 (NSW).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(672,'new-south-wales-scott-barrett-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(673,'new-south-wales-nichole-overall-statewide','nuclear','Voted AYE on the second reading of the Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions) Repeal Bill 2025 in the NSW Legislative Council on 6 May 2026 — i.e. voted to repeal NSW''s 1986 ban on uranium mining and nuclear facilities. The bill passed 21–19 and was read a third time the same day.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(674,'nt-marie-clare-boothby-brennan','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Boothby voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions allowing religious schools to hire on the basis of faith. Stated position: as Attorney-General she introduced the Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill 2025 reinstating an exception for religious schools to hire on the basis of faith and narrowing vilification provisions, saying the changes aimed to restore ''freedom of speech, especially for individuals and religious communities ... without allowing [or] condoning hate speech.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(675,'nt-marie-clare-boothby-brennan','drugs_law_order','As NT Attorney-General and Minister for Tourism and Hospitality, Boothby led the CLP government''s removal of the alcohol minimum floor price, stating the CLP is ''focused on real reforms'' and committed to alcohol policy that is ''responsible, targeted, and evidence-based'' while supporting the hospitality sector; she framed pricing controls as ineffective compared with targeted measures such as Police Auxiliary Liquor Inspectors. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(676,'nt-joshua-burgoyne-braitling','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Burgoyne voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(677,'nt-joshua-burgoyne-braitling','drugs_law_order','Burgoyne (with fellow Alice Springs MLAs) advocated tougher youth-crime measures, stating victims would ''be put first'' over what he called ''offender first'' policies and that ''youth justice must immediately be returned to Corrections'' as the body best placed to correct offending behaviour. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(678,'nt-robyn-cahill-port-darwin','drugs_law_order','As NT Minister for Child Protection, Cahill championed amending child protection legislation to prioritise child safety, stating ''above all else, the safety of children is what counts most'' and that ''if we can''t guarantee the safety of a child, it is absolutely paramount that we put that child somewhere safe''; she criticised an ''absolute reluctance'' to remove children from Aboriginal families. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(679,'nt-oly-carlson-wanguri','drugs_law_order','On her CLP profile, Carlson frames community safety and crime as her central concern, stating ''our lifestyle and community has changed, we live in fear and our choices have been taken away'' and citing an attack on her mother by youths at Casuarina as why she is ''standing up to make a change''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(680,'nt-jinson-charls-sanderson','drugs_law_order','Charls (Member for Sanderson) supports the CLP''s ''Declan''s Law'' bail reforms, saying the killing of Declan Laverty by a person on bail was ''the tragedy that pushed me to put my hand up, to work harder for the Northern Suburbs and to stand up for the safety and future of Territorians''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(681,'nt-steve-edgington-barkly','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Edgington voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(682,'nt-steve-edgington-barkly','drugs_law_order','As NT Minister for Alcohol Policy, Edgington backed new nuisance public drinking laws (police powers to fine up to $925, issue seven-day Banned Drinker Orders and confiscate alcohol), saying they aim at ''making our public spaces and parks safer and cleaner for everyone'' and will ''allow police to intervene earlier to ensure we stop this scourge in public places where alcohol is prohibited''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(683,'nt-steve-edgington-barkly','health','NT Minister for Health and Mental Health (Finocchiaro CLP government). Priorities include expanding Royal Darwin Hospital and buying private hospital beds to relieve pressure, welcoming 317 new junior doctors, nurses and midwives in 2025, and pressing the Commonwealth for a fairer funding share (NT at 31.8% vs national average). On Darwin Private Hospital he said ''if you are prepared to back the Territory, we are prepared to back you'' and made restoring private maternity services a priority.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(684,'nt-lia-finocchiaro-spillett','abortion','Finocchiaro supports a woman''s right to have an abortion and voted in favour of the legislation that decriminalised abortion in the Northern Territory and made the abortion drug RU486 more accessible for women in remote areas. This is a recorded vote on the Termination of Pregnancy Law Reform Act 2017.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(685,'nt-lia-finocchiaro-spillett','gender_lgbtq','As Chief Minister, Finocchiaro announced in October 2025 a policy to house NT prisoners according to sex assigned at birth, removing transgender women from women''s prisons, stating "If you''re born a bloke, you''re going to a men''s prison" and framing it as being about "women''s safety" and "women''s dignity"; she said the policy reversed the former Labor government''s approach allowing self-declaration. This is a stated position and announced government policy.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(686,'nt-lia-finocchiaro-spillett','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Finocchiaro voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill. Stated position: she said the 2022 changes set an ''extremely low bar'' on hate speech and that her government''s 2025 amendments would ''remove the ridiculous inclusion of offending someone as some type of discrimination,'' restoring protections for religious schools.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(687,'nt-lia-finocchiaro-spillett','drugs_law_order','As Chief Minister, Finocchiaro enacted ''Declan''s Law'' creating a presumption against bail for youth and adult violent offenders, lowered the age of criminal responsibility from 12 to 10, and championed tougher youth-crime penalties; she reported a ''38% increase in adults refused bail'' and said ''we can honour Declan''s life with stronger laws'', while rejecting evidence-based critiques: ''If your evidence[-based] approach worked, we wouldn''t be talking about this right now.'' These are stated positions plus government legislative action she led.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(688,'nt-jo-hersey-katherine','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Hersey voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(689,'nt-jo-hersey-katherine','drugs_law_order','Hersey (Member for Katherine) criticises bail laws as too lenient, saying it ''does not pass the pub test for these youth to be bailed repeatedly'' and blaming Labor for watering down bail and raising the age of criminal responsibility; she ties youth crime to truancy and calls for reinstating truancy officers. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(690,'nt-jo-hersey-katherine','education','NT Minister for Education and Training (CLP, since 2024). She is driving a shift to explicit teaching and phonics across NT government schools under the ''Boosting Literacy and Numeracy Plan'', stating ''The evidence is clear - explicit teaching works. From next year, every NT Government school will adopt this approach because our kids deserve the best start in life,'' and framing the reforms as ''about delivering results, not excuses'' with a focus on school attendance and Aboriginal student participation.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(691,'nt-clinton-howe-drysdale','drugs_law_order','Howe (Member for Drysdale) met the NT Liquor Commission seeking a review of alcohol licences at a number of Palmerston outlets to address alcohol-fuelled problems, and linked crime and anti-social behaviour partly to the density of public housing in his electorate. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(692,'nt-matthew-kerle-blain','drugs_law_order','On his CLP profile, Kerle (Member for Blain) makes community safety his primary priority, stating ''we must first deliver community safety'' and committing to ''strengthen the laws, empower our police, tackle cost of living and move our economy forwards''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(693,'nt-gerard-maley-nelson','voluntary_assisted_dying','Then-Acting Chief Minister Maley said he supports the principles of voluntary assisted dying but would ask his constituents before voting, and confirmed members would be allowed a conscience vote. No recorded vote has occurred. Stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(694,'nt-gerard-maley-nelson','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Maley voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(695,'nt-gerard-maley-nelson','drugs_law_order','As Deputy Chief Minister and Minister for Corrections, Maley is fast-tracking prison expansion to manage ''more than 400 additional prisoners'' since the August 2024 election, saying ''all options are on the table to address workforce challenges'' and ''this isn''t just a corrections issue – it''s a justice system issue''; he supports the government''s bail crackdown including a presumption against bail and mandatory electronic monitoring for repeat serious offenders. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(696,'nt-brian-o-gallagher-karama','drugs_law_order','O''Gallagher (Member for Karama) backed establishing a permanent Northern Suburbs Youth Hub, saying ''this has been needed for a long time and this new facility will give youth a safe, vibrant place to connect, learn and grow'', framing youth services as part of the government''s community-safety agenda. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(697,'nt-khoda-patel-casuarina','drugs_law_order','Patel (Member for Casuarina) identifies youth crime and anti-social behaviour as top concerns for local businesses and fought to relocate the Northern Suburbs Youth Hub, saying he wanted to provide youth ''a safe, active, and positive place that our youth can truly be proud of''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(698,'nt-tanzil-rahman-fong-lim','faith','In a speech on his official website, Tanzil Rahman explicitly states that he subscribes to the Muslim faith: "that is the faith to which I subscribe as well."',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(699,'nt-bill-yan-namatjira','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Yan (listed as William Yan) voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(700,'nt-bill-yan-namatjira','drugs_law_order','Yan (Member for Namatjira), a former Alice Springs Correctional Centre manager, emphasises rehabilitation and addressing root causes, stating on his CLP profile he is ''fighting as part of the CLP Team that will address root causes of crime'' and that rehabilitation and skills training reduce reoffending; he also co-advocated returning youth justice to Corrections and tougher bail. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(701,'nt-laurie-zio-fannie-bay','drugs_law_order','Zio (Member for Fannie Bay) stated her support for mandatory sentencing for assaults on frontline workers, posting ''Like this post if you support mandatory sentencing''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(702,'nt-chansey-paech-gwoja','abortion','Paech supported the 2017 Termination of Pregnancy Law Reform Bill during the parliamentary debate, tabling and criticising as ''offensive and racist'' a Right to Life media release about Aboriginal population control. This reflects a stated position in support during the debate on the bill, which passed 20-4.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(703,'nt-chansey-paech-gwoja','gender_lgbtq','In his maiden speech to the NT Legislative Assembly on 19 October 2016, Paech said "I am young, I am gay, I am black," called for same-sex marriage recognition ("I look forward to the day when this country will recognise my rights as equal rights, when I too can marry in my country"), and stated "I will never allow or tolerate discrimination, homophobia or hate speech in this Assembly." This is a stated position; Paech is the first openly gay Indigenous MP in Australia.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(704,'nt-chansey-paech-gwoja','religious_freedom','Recorded vote / sponsor: as Labor Attorney-General Paech introduced and voted for the 2022 Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill that removed religious-school hiring exemptions, describing criticism of its hate-speech provisions as ''fearmongering.'' Stated position: in 2025 he opposed the CLP''s amendments, posting that ''we do not support the CLP''s attempt to water down our anti-discrimination laws.''',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(705,'nt-chansey-paech-gwoja','drugs_law_order','Paech, as former Labor Attorney-General, introduced laws raising the age of criminal responsibility and reforming adult mandatory sentencing; as Shadow Attorney-General he opposed the CLP''s bail changes and lowering the age to 10, saying ''changing bail laws is not addressing root causes'' and calling the legislation a ''purely punitive measure that will ultimately make our communities less safe'' that sets children up to ''become career criminals''. This is a stated position plus prior legislative action.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(706,'nt-selena-uibo-arnhem','abortion','Uibo supported the 2017 Termination of Pregnancy Law Reform Bill, stating in the debate that she stood ''as a young Aboriginal woman who wants the same rights as my fellow female Australians in every other state and territory.'' This reflects a stated position in support during the debate on the bill, which passed 20-4.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(707,'nt-selena-uibo-arnhem','voluntary_assisted_dying','Labor Opposition Leader Uibo supports voluntary assisted dying; on 13 October 2025 she submitted a draft VAD bill to the government, urging it to adopt the legislation rather than ''waste more time''. The government declined to use her bill. No recorded vote has occurred. Stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(708,'nt-selena-uibo-arnhem','gender_lgbtq','As Opposition Leader during parliamentary question time in October 2025, Uibo challenged the government''s transgender prisoner policy, telling the Chief Minister that despite the announced ban, "internal department documents state that you have not, and you still operate your government under the 2021 version four directive." This is a stated position recorded in parliament.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(709,'nt-selena-uibo-arnhem','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Uibo voted in favour of Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill. Stated position: as Labor leader she said in 2025 that the CLP government''s plan to remove vilification protections is ''unacceptable'' and out of step with other Australian jurisdictions and international human rights conventions.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(710,'nt-selena-uibo-arnhem','drugs_law_order','As Opposition Leader, Uibo criticised the CLP''s repeated youth justice and bail rewrites as ''chaos disguised as policy'', with ''no consultation, no evidence, no real plan'', saying ''each time, they''ve ignored expert advice. And each time, crime has gotten worse'', and noting the government ''scrapped the Minimum Unit Price making alcohol cheaper''; she advocates early intervention, diversion and trauma-informed care. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(711,'nt-dheran-young-daly','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Young voted in favour of Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion and broadened vilification protections.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(712,'nt-justine-davis-johnston','voluntary_assisted_dying','Independent member Davis supports voluntary assisted dying; she moved the original NT Legislative Assembly motion (13 May 2025) to progress VAD that led to the parliamentary inquiry, and chairs the NT VAD working group. No recorded vote has occurred. Stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(713,'nt-justine-davis-johnston','gender_lgbtq','In October 2025, independent MLA Justine Davis opposed the government''s changes affecting transgender people in prisons, stating in an SBS interview "There is no need for these changes and, in fact, they are going to potentially cause harm." This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(714,'nt-justine-davis-johnston','drugs_law_order','Davis (Independent, Johnston) opposed lowering the age of criminal responsibility to 10, calling it ''a bad day for democracy in the Northern Territory'', apologising to her community, and warning the NT would not ''be the only country in the world that treats 10-year-olds as criminals''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(715,'nt-yingiya-mark-guyula-mulka','abortion','Guyula was one of four members who voted against the 2017 Termination of Pregnancy Law Reform Bill that decriminalised abortion in the Northern Territory. This is a recorded vote against the bill, which passed 20-4.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(716,'nt-yingiya-mark-guyula-mulka','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Guyula, as an independent, voted in favour of Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill, which removed exemptions that had allowed faith-based schools to hire staff sharing the school''s religion and broadened vilification protections.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(717,'nt-yingiya-mark-guyula-mulka','drugs_law_order','Guyula (Independent, Mulka) opposed the CLP''s bail laws and lowering the age of criminal responsibility, saying ''we want to see community-led solutions'' and that the NT ''locks up almost four times more children than the next highest jurisdiction'' and the changes ''will jail more First Nations adults and children than ever before''; he said he was ''disappointed to be a part of this Parliament that is lowering the age''. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(718,'nt-robyn-lambley-araluen','voluntary_assisted_dying','Independent member and Assembly Speaker Lambley opposes proceeding with voluntary assisted dying in the NT, saying ''I don''t think we''re ready. Maybe we''ll never be ready in the Territory'' and ''It will be a disaster... We just need to take it at our own pace,'' citing difficulties educating remote Indigenous communities. No recorded vote has occurred. Stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(719,'nt-robyn-lambley-araluen','gender_lgbtq','During the August 2024 NT election campaign, the Australian Christian Lobby recorded that independent MLA Robyn Lambley (along with all CLP candidates) supported a review into the medical and surgical care of gender-diverse children; as Speaker she subsequently tabled the ACL''s petition (17-18 October 2024) calling for the suspension of gender-affirming treatments for children in the NT. Tabling a petition is a procedural duty; her support for a review is the recorded stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(720,'nt-robyn-lambley-araluen','religious_freedom','Recorded vote: in November 2022 (14th Assembly) Lambley, as an independent, voted against Labor''s Anti-Discrimination Amendment Bill that removed religious-school hiring exemptions. Stated position: in the Australian Christian Lobby''s 2024 NT election questionnaire she answered affirmatively to supporting repeal of the 2022 changes to protect faith-based schools, repeal of offence-based provisions, and completely protecting speech from the pulpit.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(721,'nt-robyn-lambley-araluen','drugs_law_order','Lambley (Independent, Araluen) has long pressed for stronger action on crime and alcohol in Central Australia: she moved (and was ejected from Parliament over) a bid for a non-partisan crime committee, saying ''we can either continue to go down the path that we''re on... and see crime escalate... or we can do something different'', and earlier advocated an emergency 8pm-6am youth curfew and reinstating ''personal and parental responsibility'' laws. This is a stated position.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(722,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','abortion','Recorded vote: voted Aye (in favour) on the third reading of the Termination of Pregnancy Bill 2018, which decriminalised abortion in Queensland (passed 50-41 on 17 October 2018).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(723,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','voluntary_assisted_dying','Recorded vote: voted FOR the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021, which passed the Queensland Legislative Assembly 61-30 on 16 September 2021 in a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(724,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','religious_freedom','Voted in favour of the Respect at Work and Other Matters Amendment Bill 2024 on its third reading (10 September 2024). The Bill retained, rather than removed, exemptions allowing faith-based schools and religious bodies to discriminate in employment, after the Labor government withdrew its earlier proposal to narrow them.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(725,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','drugs_law_order','As a sitting Labor member, recorded as voting in favour of the Making Queensland Safer Bill 2024 (Adult Crime, Adult Time) on its passage on 12 December 2024, when only Greens MP Michael Berkman and independent Sandy Bolton voted against.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(726,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','sex_work','Voted YES (Ayes) on the second reading of the Criminal Code (Decriminalising Sex Work) and Other Legislation Amendment Bill 2024, which decriminalised sex work in Queensland. The named division was carried 49–35 on 2 May 2024; Leeanne Enoch is recorded in the Ayes.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(727,'queensland-leeanne-enoch-algester','first_nations','Voted NOE on the second reading of the Brisbane Olympic and Paralympic Games Arrangements and Other Legislation Amendment Bill 2024 (28 November 2024), opposing the omnibus bill that repealed the Path to Treaty Act 2023 (which ended Queensland''s First Nations Treaty Institute and Truth-telling and Healing Inquiry). The bill passed 53 to 35.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(728,'queensland-bart-mellish-aspley','abortion','Recorded vote: voted Aye (in favour) on the third reading of the Termination of Pregnancy Bill 2018, which decriminalised abortion in Queensland (passed 50-41 on 17 October 2018).',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(729,'queensland-bart-mellish-aspley','voluntary_assisted_dying','Recorded vote: voted AGAINST the Voluntary Assisted Dying Bill 2021 (one of three Labor members to do so), which nonetheless passed the Queensland Legislative Assembly 61-30 on 16 September 2021 in a conscience vote.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(730,'queensland-bart-mellish-aspley','religious_freedom','Voted in favour of the Respect at Work and Other Matters Amendment Bill 2024 on its third reading (10 September 2024). The Bill retained, rather than removed, exemptions allowing faith-based schools and religious bodies to discriminate in employment, after the Labor government withdrew its earlier proposal to narrow them.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(731,'queensland-bart-mellish-aspley','drugs_law_order','As a sitting Labor member, recorded as voting in favour of the Making Queensland Safer Bill 2024 (Adult Crime, Adult Time) on its passage on 12 December 2024, when only Greens MP Michael Berkman and independent Sandy Bolton voted against.',1);
INSERT INTO "position" VALUES(732,'queensland-bart-mellish-aspley','sex_work','Voted YES (Ayes) on the second reading of the Criminal Code (Decriminalising Sex Work) and Other Legislation Amendment Bill 2024, which decriminalised sex work in Queensland. The named division was carried 49–35 on 2 May 2024; Bart Mellish is recorded in the Ayes.',1);
